 of the strangest formal features of canonical American texts. These authors' attempts to found social life on something other than mental states not only invite us to revise our assumptions about the centrality of mind reading and empathy to the novel as a form; they can also help us understand more contemporary concepts in social cognition, including gaslighting and learned helplessness, with more conceptual rigor and historical depth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPhilosophy of mind in literature. 0aSocial perception in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican literature.  aUnited States.  acognition.  afiction.  anineteenth century.  aphilosophy of mind.  apsychology.  atheory of mind (ToM).08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363204240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503632042423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503632042/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles